reply_text:
@KarimanShamaeva​​⁠ I didn’t say there’s a category of people that become victims of trafficking, I said traffickers typically target young women from broken families, which is one hundred percent true. Of course they’ll do what they can to avoid a manhunt. A 23 year old American from a stable family would not be a normal target, and certainly not when she’s on board a ship, sharing a room with her parents and bother. That would be the last place someone would want to organize a kidnapping. And why would anyone kidnap someone on a ship unless they knew they could walk off without being detained. That indicates a massive conspiracy with Caribbean Cruise. Do you really think it sounds reasonable to suggest Caribbean Cruise, with all their wealth, would conspire to kidnap one American woman on board their ship. Pardon me, but that’s ridiculous. They made some mistakes after she was reported missing, but for the most part they did their due diligence. And so what if they were a little cold about it. That doesn’t make them criminals. And remember that’s only how it was depicted in the documentary. In real life the family sued Caribbean, and they got nothing…the case was dismissed. Was the justice system in on this conspiracy too?

I’m not trying to start a fight. I just don’t like seeing people who are likely innocent getting accused of bad crimes. Amy likely committed suicide. It’s sad for her family, but it’s just a simple fact. Maybe it was because of her recent relationship going sour, as indicated with the message in the bottle to her girlfriend from a month before the cruise, as talked about in the documentary. Maybe her family didn’t understand her, being gay and all. It was the nineties: that kind of thing wasn’t as accepted back then. I’m not saying they didn’t love her: it’s obvious they did. 

I know that Yellow, the base player who danced with her, said in a recent interview that her family made her go on the trip. He seemed like a nice and credible person in this interview, and his reputation has been tampered because of the Amy incident, (people think he had something to do with her disappearance). Anyways, Amy was in the sixth deck: that’s about 200 feet up. That would further support the suicide theory, because at that height it would likely be painless. Again, it was very sad and tragic incident, but suicide is still the most reasonable explanation.
